result.execSummary:
The defendant Dean E. Prindle was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged or terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of any restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  If the defendant is placed on probation or released to extended supervision, IT IS ORDERED that the defendant pay supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections.

Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, the bar areas of restaurants. Defendant may not possess or consume any alcohol, nor be anywhere alcohol is available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.

Not to possess or consume any controlled substances.   Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Not to possess any prescription medications of any kind unless those have been prescribed to the defendant by a physician, and in that case, the defendant shall take such medications only as prescribed.  Defendant shall not alter the form of any prescription prior to, or in conjunction with, ingestion.  

Defendant to be subject to random testing by his agent.

No violent, abusive, threatening or disorderly contact with anyone who is involved with his daughter's case, including but not limited to the Jackson County Department of Health & Human Services, or the victim.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  

Defendant must comply with mental health treatment recommendations by his physician.  Must follow doctor's recommendations exactly.  Must sign releases to agent of all of his mental and physical conditions providers.  

Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody, with Attorney Prior.  Victim notification complied with.  Victim present in courtroom.  Defendant plead no contest to count 3 as a repeater.  Counts 1 and 2, dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court recited the charges and possible penalties on the count he plead to.  Defendant understood.  Court confirmed the repeater allegation with the defendant and Attorney Prior.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the pleas. Found guilty of disorderly conduct as a repeater, contrary to 947.01(1).  Victim made a statement.  She wasn't aware Counts 1 and 2 were going to be dismissed.  State responded.  Court questioned whether victim rights were fully complied with.  State responded.  Victim understood the read in. Joint recommendation for:  probation 1 year.  Anger management, as recommended by mental health providers and the agent.    Not to possess or consume any controlled substances.   Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Not to possess any prescription medications of any kind unless those have been prescribed to the defendant by a physician, and in that case, the defendant shall take such medications only as prescribed.  Defendant shall not alter the form of any prescription prior to, or in conjunction with, ingestion.  Must comply with mental health treatment recommendations by his physician.    No violent, abusive, threatening or disorderly contact with the department or the victim.
